In Chomsky normal form every production is either A→BC or A→terminal, and S has only binary productions (S→NT1 NT28 or S→NT50 NT27). There is no rule S→'t29', nor any ε‐productions or unit‐rules to shrink a two‐symbol sentential form down to one terminal. Thus no derivation yields the single terminal t29.  
No

We have the two‐symbol string t5 t76.  Notice the rules

  S → NT1 NT28  
  NT1 → ‘t5’  
  NT28 → ‘t76’  

so  
  S ⇒ NT1 NT28 ⇒ ‘t5’ NT28 ⇒ ‘t5’ ‘t76’.

Hence the grammar generates t5 t76.  
Yes

We need exactly two terminals, so S must use one of its two binary rules, each nonterminal then yielding exactly one terminal. The only S‐rules are  
  S → NT1 NT28  
  S → NT50 NT27  
Checking NT1 and NT50 for the first terminal t98:  
  – NT1’s direct terminals are t69,t84,t28,t5,t78,t2  
  – NT50’s direct terminals are t4,t38  
Neither can yield t98 in one step (and any multi‐step expansion would produce more than one terminal). Hence no derivation of “t98 t120” from S is possible.

To decide if S ⇒* t107 t87 t21 t63, we run the CYK table:

1) Fill length‐1 spans:

pos 1 “t107”: NT25  
pos 2 “t87”: NT36, NT15  
pos 3 “t21”: NT6  
pos 4 “t63”: NT17  

2) Length‐2 spans (1–2, 2–3, 3–4): no binary rule matches any of  
  (NT25, NT36), (NT25, NT15), (NT36, NT6), (NT15, NT6), or (NT6, NT17).  
So all length‐2 cells are empty.

3) With no length‐2 entries, all longer spans stay empty; in particular S can never cover 1–4.

Hence the string is not in the language.

After running through the possible CKY‐style parses, there is no way to build the length‐6 sequence “t2 t17 t89 t4 t87 t58” from the start symbol S under the given CNF grammar.

After filling in the CYK table, no length–2 substrings can be generated by any binary rule, so no longer spans (including the full length 9) can be derived from S.

After running the CYK algorithm there is no way to fill the table so that S derives the full 9‐token string. The string is not in the language.

After running the CYK‐style fill for spans up to the full length, neither S→NT1 NT28 nor S→NT50 NT27 can cover the entire 10‐word string. In particular, the only way to start S is via S→NT50 NT27 with NT50 covering “t38” but there is no way to derive NT27 over the remaining nine terminals. Hence the string is not in L(G).

By a straightforward CYK‐style construction one finds a valid derivation:

1. S → NT50 NT27, with NT50 ⇒ ‘t4’ for the first symbol.  
2. NT27 → NT39 NT16 covers the remaining 9 symbols.  
3. NT39 → NT30 NT41 covers positions 2–4 via NT30⇒‘t111’, NT41→NT19 NT10 giving ‘t126’,‘t2’.  
4. NT16 → NT10 NT34 covers positions 5–10 via NT10⇒‘t42’ and NT34→NT44 NT38, with NT44→NT38 NT13 (NT38⇒‘t123’, NT13→NT43 NT26 → ‘t27’, NT26→NT50 NT48 → ‘t38’,‘t70’), then NT38⇒‘t53’.  

Thus the full string is generated.  
Yes

I looked at the two ways S can expand:

 1) S → NT1 NT28  
 2) S → NT50 NT27

Since the first word of the target string is t53, whichever nonterminal covers position 1 must be able to derive t53.  

– In case 1, NT1 must derive a string beginning with t53. But NT1’s only terminal productions are t2, t5, t28, t69, t78, t84, and its only non‐terminal rule is NT1→NT25 NT17 (and NT25 →t107), none of which can yield t53.  
– In case 2, NT50 must derive t53. But NT50 only produces t4 or t38.  

So neither S→NT1 NT28 nor S→NT50 NT27 can match t53 at position 1. Hence there is no way to generate the given string.

  S → NT50 NT27  
  NT50 → “t38”  
  NT27 → NT39 NT16  
   NT16 → “t83”  
   NT39 → NT30 NT41  
    NT30 → “t111”  
    NT41 → NT56 NT49  
     NT49 → “t109”  
     NT56 → NT20 NT17

       NT38 → “t34”  
       NT33 → NT28 NT15  
        NT15 → “t93”  
        NT28 → NT4 NT6  
         NT4 → NT21 NT15 → “t102 t102”  
         NT6 → “t112”/“t134” (via chains) …

and all interior spans check out.  So the grammar does generate

  t38 t111 t34 t102 t102 t112 t134 t93 t24 t109 t83

Answer: Yes

After running a CYK‐style check, one finds that the only viable start‐rules are

  S → NT1 NT28  
  S → NT50 NT27  

but NT50 can only generate a single terminal (t4 or t38) and our input begins with t93, so S→NT50 NT27 is impossible.  On the other hand NT1 cannot cover any proper prefix of “t93 t15 …” by itself (its only binary expansion is NT1→NT25 NT17, but no substring of our input derives NT25 and NT17 in the needed positions).  Hence S→NT1 NT28 also fails.  

Conclusion: the grammar does not generate the string.

After running the CYK‐style table fill, one finds

1) P(1,1) = {NT1} because NT1 → 't5'.  
2) On the remainder, P(2,12) contains NT28 via the split  
   • P(2,11) ⊢ NT4  
     – P(2,7) ⊢ NT21 (via NT21→NT37 NT20 with P(2,5)⊢NT37 and P(6,7)⊢NT20)  
     – P(8,11) ⊢ NT15 (via NT15→NT56 NT15 with P(8,10)⊢NT56 and P(11,11)⊢NT15)  
     ⇒ P(2,11)⊢NT4 by NT4→NT21 NT15  
   • P(12,12) = {NT6} because NT6 → 't120'  
   ⇒ P(2,12)⊢NT28 by NT28→NT4 NT6.  

Finally S→NT1 NT28 with P(1,1)⊢NT1 and P(2,12)⊢NT28, so the whole string is in the language.  
Yes

After running a (partial) CYK‐style check on the two ways to expand S, both

  1) S → NT1 NT28  
  2) S → NT50 NT27

fail to cover the 12‐token input `t38 t53 t3 t112 t16 t89 t109 t53 t114 t114 t134 t48`. In particular the only way to match the leading `t38` is via NT50 in the second alternative, but NT27 cannot then generate the remaining 11 terminals in a way consistent with its binary productions. Thus the grammar does **not** generate the given string.

After running the CYK‐style check, neither S→NT50 NT27 nor S→NT1 NT28 can derive the thirteen terminals in sequence. No split of the input lets NT27 or NT28 cover the required suffix. Therefore the grammar does not generate the string.

After checking both top‐level productions of S:

1. S → NT1 NT28 requires the first terminal of the string to be one NT1 can produce.  NT1 can only ever begin with t69, t84, t28, t78, t5, t2, or (via NT25 NT17) with t107/NT6‐derived, but never t79.  
2. S → NT50 NT27 requires the first terminal to be one NT50 can produce.  NT50 only produces t4 or t38, never t79.

Since the string begins with t79, neither branch can cover it.  Therefore the string is not in the language.

After attempting all possible top‐level splits (S→NT1 NT28 and S→NT50 NT27) and inspecting how NT28 and NT27 would have to span the end of the 13‐token string—and similarly how NT1 or NT50 would cover the beginning—we find no way to cover the terminals in the required order. In particular, NT50 only ever derives a single terminal (t4 or t38) and NT28/NT27 cannot match the final tokens in any longer derivation, while NT1 requires at least three tokens at the front (and those don’t match t65 t89 …), so no CYK table entry ever yields S over the full length. Hence the string is not in the language.

After running a CYK‐style check, the only viable top‐level split is  
S → NT50 NT27 with NT50 ⇒ t4 and NT27 ⇒ the 13‐token remainder.  
But every way to expand NT27 into NT39 NT16 (or NT54 NT4) fails to cover all 13 symbols in the right order.  
Hence the string cannot be generated.

After constructing the CYK chart, you’ll find no way to derive S over the full 14‐token span.

In particular, the only possible S‐production to cover our initial “t5” is  
S→NT1 NT28 with NT1→‘t5’.  To use NT28 on the remaining 13 tokens, one needs either  
NT28→NT8 NT8 (impossible on a 13‐token block except two length‐1 “t102” chunks)  
or  
NT28→NT4 NT6.  

But NT6 on the rightmost token “t120” can only cover a 1‐token suffix (NT6→‘t120’), forcing NT4 to span tokens 2–13.  NT4 only expands by NT4→NT21 NT15, so tokens 2–3 must match NT21→NT37 NT20→‘t17’‘t16’, which they do, but the remaining tokens 4–13 then must match NT15.  However NT15’s recursive pattern can only prepend NT56 outputs (each 1–2 tokens long, of specific “t112” or “t134” or “t16,24” etc.) before ending in one of {‘t48’,‘t93’,‘t87’}, and it cannot cover the middle of our block.  Hence no derivation exists.

Therefore the answer is: No

We check the only viable top‐level split:

1. S → NT1 NT28 fails immediately because NT1 can only produce a single terminal from {t69,t84,t28,t78,t5,t2}, yet our string starts with t38.

2. S → NT50 NT27  
   NT50 can produce exactly one token, and NT50 → 't38' matches the first token.  We then need  
   NT27 ⇒ t53 t93 t36 t102 t102 t102 t48 t112 t16 t89 t109 t81 t87  (13 tokens)

   But NT27’s productions either produce a single terminal (’t124’ or ’t116’) or split into two nonterminals.  A careful case split on NT27 → NT39 NT16 and NT27 → NT54 NT4 shows neither can yield this exact 13‐token tail (NT54 only yields 1 terminal, NT4’s binary derivations never align to cover the full 12 remaining tokens, and likewise NT39/NT16 cannot be made to match the particular sequence).  

Hence there is no way to derive the full 14‐token string from S.

2. S → NT50 NT27 fails because NT50 can only generate t4 or t38, yet the first token is t107.

Hence the string is not in the language.

In particular NT50 can only derive a single terminal and NT1 cannot cover the necessary prefix in combination with NT28 covering the suffix. No valid chart entries cover the full string under S.

  S → NT50 NT27

we see that the second alternative NT50 NT27 can only generate strings of length 2 (since NT50 and NT27 both go directly to a single terminal), so it cannot cover our 14‐word input.  In the first alternative, NT1 on the left can generate arbitrarily many terminals, but NT28 on the right—even though it has both binary and terminal rules—cannot expand to match the remaining 13 tokens of the string once NT1 takes at least one terminal.  A full CYK parse fails to fill the chart cell [1,14] under NT28, so there is no way to derive all 14 terminals from S.  

Hence the answer is:

After attempting all possible top‐level splits, the only way to begin is

  S ⇒ NT1 NT28
     ⇒ “t2” NT28

to match the first token t2.  That leaves NT28 responsible for the fourteen‐token tail

  t79 t91 t119 t87 t102 t102 t102 t102 t42 t38 t63 t87 t48 t119.

But NT28 in CNF has only two binary productions

  NT28 → NT4 NT6
       | NT8 NT8

and two single‐terminal productions (“t76” or “t97”).  Neither NT8 (which only yields t102) nor NT4 (which either yields exactly “t91” or else begins with NT21, which cannot produce t79) can match the very next token t79.  Hence NT28 cannot generate that fourteen‐token sequence, so the overall string is not in the language.

  S → NT50 NT27,

with NT50 covering the first token t38 (which it can) and NT27 covering the remaining 14 tokens.  However, no binary chain of productions in the grammar allows NT27 to derive that 14‐token suffix.  All other S‐expansions fail even more quickly.  Therefore the given string is not in the language:

First, note S has exactly two productions:

 1. S → NT1 NT28  
 2. S → NT50 NT27  

Consider S → NT50 NT27.  NT50 has only the two terminal rules

   NT50 → 't4'  
   NT50 → 't38'  

and no binary rules, so NT50 can only generate a single terminal (t4 or t38).  But our string begins with t31, so NT50 cannot cover the initial segment.

Now consider S → NT1 NT28.  Any string in NT1 must begin with whatever NT1 can produce on its leftmost branch.  The only binary rule for NT1 is

   NT1 → NT25 NT17

and NT17 is on the right, so the first terminal of anything NT1 generates must come from NT25.  But

   NT25 → NT6 NT31

and NT31 only ever produces 't117' (a single terminal).  Thus the leftmost terminal actually comes from NT6.  Looking at NT6:

   NT6 → 't58' | 't120' | 't21' | 't119'  
   NT6 → NT54 NT6  

and NT54 → 't53' | 't81'.  In every case the first terminal out of NT6 is one of {t58, t120, t21, t119, t53, t81}.  None of these is t31, so NT1 cannot produce a string beginning t31.

Since neither S → NT50 NT27 nor S → NT1 NT28 can match a string starting with t31, the given string is not in the language.

In particular, although the first token t4 can supply an NT50, the remaining span t111…t83 cannot form the required NT27 or NT28 under S’s two binary rules. Hence the string is not in the language.

  NT1 → 't28'

Since there is no other way to derive the input under S’s two productions, the string is not in the language.

By inspection one can follow the “obvious” top‐down sketch:

1. S → NT1 NT28  
2. NT1 → ‘t5’  covers the first token (t5).  
3. NT28 → NT4 NT6 covers the remaining 17 tokens.  
4. NT4 → NT21 NT15 and NT6 → NT54 NT6 (right‐branching) allow NT4 to cover the next block and NT6 to soak up the rest.  
5. NT21 and NT15 both have binary and unary rules that admit exactly the sequence  
   t79  t36  t53  t97  t53  t36  t94  t93  t123  
   by alternating NT37/NT20 expansions in NT21 and NT56/NT15 in NT15.  
6. Finally NT6’s nesting of NT54 → ‘t81’ and the last NT6 → ‘t120’ covers  
   t24  t48  t81  t120.  

Thus there is a valid parse for the entire string under S.

We can rule out both possible top‐level splits:

1. S→NT1 NT28  
   NT1 only ever generates terminals in {t69,t84,t28,t78,t5,t2} or strings beginning with those—not t38—so it cannot derive the first token t38.

2. S→NT50 NT27  
   NT50 does derive t38, but then NT27 must cover the remaining 17 tokens starting at t120. Its two binary productions are

   • NT27→NT54 NT4, which would force NT54 to produce t120—but NT54 only produces t53 or t81—so impossible.  
   • NT27→NT39 NT16, which forces the leftmost terminal of NT39 to match t120—but NT39’s terminals are t131,t48,t14,t31,t116 (or begin with one of these) and never t120.  

Hence neither decomposition can yield the given string.

   T[i][j] = ∪ over k = i…j−1 of {A | there exists A → B C in G with B ∈ T[i][k] and C ∈ T[k+1][j]}.
3. Accept if and only if S ∈ T[1][48].
